## Note on Calendars

- All dates in the book use the **Common Era (CE/AD)** calendar —
  the Gregorian calendar reformed by Pope Gregory XIII in 1582
- Orthodox and Eastern churches retained the older **Julian** ("Old Style")
  calendar for religious purposes; Orthodox Christmas falls on
  7 January of the Gregorian calendar

### The Muslim (Hijri) Calendar
- **Muslim era (AH)** dates from **16 July 622 CE** — the beginning of
  the Arab year of the **Hijra** (Muhammad's migration from Mecca to Medina)
- Purely **lunar**: 12 months, 354 days — no adjustment to solar year
- Religious occasions (Ramadan, Pilgrimage) traverse the entire solar year
- Conversion ratio: roughly **103 Hijri years = 100 Gregorian years**

### Solar Adaptations of the Hijri Calendar
- The purely lunar Hijri calendar was inconvenient for fiscal/
  administrative use; Muslim governments created solar hybrid systems:
  1. **Turkish *Maliye* (financial year)**: Julian year + Hijri era,
     introduced into Ottoman revenue administration in 1789 CE
  2. **Persian solar year**: introduced 1925; based on Hijra but
     calculated in solar years using old Iranian month names;
     to convert to Gregorian, add 622 (for dates 1 Jan–21 Mar)
     or 621 (for dates 21 Mar–31 Dec)

### The Jewish Calendar
- Traditionally dated from the **creation of the world**
- 12 lunar months, adjusted to the solar year by intercalation
  of an extra month at seven points in a 19-year cycle
- Used for religious purposes and some civil purposes in Israel
- Jewish New Year 5756 = 25 September 1995 (CE)

